StringWithMarkup.String: Shikimic acid is a cyclohexenecarboxylic acid that is cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 4 and 5 (the 3R,4S,5R stereoisomer). StringWithMarkup.String: Shikimic acid's production and use as active component in the flotation reagent Quebracho and its presence in bracken fern (Pteridium aquilinum) may result in its release to the environment. If released into the atmosphere, shikimic acid will exist predominantly in the particulate phase the ambient atmosphere, based on an estimated vapor pressure of 5.0X10-9 mm Hg at 25 °C. Vapor phase shikimic acid is degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals with a half-life of about 6.3 hours. An estimated Koc value of 6 suggests that shikimic acid will have very high mobility in soil. Volatilization from moist soil is not expected based upon an estimated Henry's Law constant of 2.7X10-14 atm-cu m/mole. Volatilization from dry soil surfaces should not be important given the vapor pressure of this compound. Under anaerobic conditions, microorganisms from the genera Pseudomonas, Flavobacterium, Achromobacter, and Xanthomonas aerobically degraded shikimic acid with an oxygen uptake of approximately 150 ul after 120 minutes. In water, shikimic acid is not expected to adsorb to sediment or particulate matter based on its Koc value. This compound is not expected to volatilize from water surfaces given its estimated Henry's Law constant. Bioconcentration in aquatic organisms should be low based upon an estimated BCF value of 0.74. Given the commercial uses of shikimic acid, human exposure appears to be likely from occupational situations through dermal routes. The general population may be exposed to shikimic acid via ingestion of food and drinking water and other products containing shikimic acid. (SRC)

Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.
